TY  - JOUR
AU  - Papanikolaou, Dimitris
AU  - Schmidt, Lawrence D W
T1  - Working Remotely and the Supply-Side Impact of COVID-19
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/raab026
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
SP  - 53
EP  - 111
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - We analyze the supply-side disruptions associated with COVID-19. We find that sectors in which a higher fraction of the workforce is not able to work remotely experienced greater declines in employment and expected revenue growth, worse stock market performance, and higher likelihood of default. The stock market overweights low-exposure industries. Thus, our findings cast light on the disconnect between stock market indices and aggregate outcomes. We combine these ex ante heterogeneous industry exposures with daily financial market data to create a stock return portfolio that tracks news about the supply-side disruptions resulting from the pandemic. (JEL G12, D22, H25, J20, E00)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/raab026
ER  - 



